Rogue 3270 (Legacy version of Pyrogue)
Implemented by Andrew Butler
Spring Semester 2025 @ Iowa State University

About this legacy branch:
Rogue 3270 is the predecessor to PyRogue, and is the result of a series 
of assignments for a class at Iowa State University in the Spring of 2025.
This code is suboptimal for a few reasons:
  - Development was often rushed due to how busy I was.
  - We started with exclusively C code, then moved to C++. This means the
    OOP structure is very much so unoptimized, if only b/c I never fixed it.
  - The control structure was rushed, and was built with a "just get it to work"
    mentality; this is actually one of the main reasons PyRogue exists.
Also worth noting:
  - Some pieces of code (namely heap.h/.c) were provided by Prof. Jeremy Sheaffer
  - Error/Fault prevention is spotty at best, so buggy behavior is possible.


To run Rogue 3270:
- Navigate to directory of files
- run makefile using 'make'
- run compiled/linked file with '/rogue'.
- Might need to sort out dependencies (ncurses, pkg-config)


There are four possible command line arguments:
'-s | --save' will save the dungeon to file upon completion of the program.
'-l | --load' will read a dungeon from file when starting program.
'-n | --nummon <count>' specifies how many monsters to generate in the dungeon.
'-p | --parse' prints parsed monster & object definitions to terminal, then ends.

The game has the following key binds:
================================   MOVEMENT   ================================
  7 or y : Attempt to move PC one cell to the upper left.
  8 or k : Attempt to move PC one cell up.
  9 or u : Attempt to move PC one cell to the upper right.
  6 or l : Attempt to move PC one cell to the right.
  3 or n : Attempt to move PC one cell to the lower right.
  2 or j : Attempt to move PC one cell down.
  1 or b : Attempt to move PC one cell to the lower left.
  4 or h : Attempt to move PC one cell to the left.
  > : Attempt to go down stairs. Works only if standing on down staircase.
  < : Attempt to go up stairs. Works only if standing on up staircase.
  5 or space or . : Rest for a turn NPCs still move.

================================   INVENTORY  ================================
  m : Display a list of monsters in the dungeon, with their symbol and 
      position relative to the PC (e.g., "c, 2 north and 14 west").
  i : Gives item names that are in each of the PC's carry slots.
  e : Opens a menu that lists the item names that are equipped by the PC.
  , : Attempts to pick up an item that the PC is standing over, placing in 
      next available carry slot. Will display message on success/failure.
  w : Asks for a carry slot, then attempts to equip the item in that slot.
  t : Aks for an equipment slot, then attempts move it to carry slot. 
  x : Asks for a carry slot, then attempts to destroy  the specified item.
  d : Asks for a carry slot, then attempts to drop the specified item.

================================  INFORMATION ================================
  L : Enters target mode; 'L' again shows information about targeted monster.
  I : Asks for carry slot, then displays information about it.

================================    CHEATS    ================================
  f : Toggles the 'fog of war' effect.
  g : Enters teleport mode to allow PC to move across the map; Pressing 'g' 
      again teleports to cursor location; 'r' teleports to a random location.
  z : Shows distance maps, or shows monster's path while inspecting one.

================================ MISCELLANOUS ================================
  up arrow : Scrolls menu up, if scrolling is available/ necessary.
  down arrow: Scrolls menu down, if scrolling is available/ necessary.
  esc : Returns to character control from the various menus.
  Q : Quit to main menu or quit game.

Things of note with v1.10:
  - v1.10 included main menu, replay on game over, dodge/def/hit bonuses, bugfixes
  - Known issue: Quitting from main menu sometimes doesn't clear the screen correctly; 
    This is both inconsistent and doesn't harm anything, so I'm not too worried about it.
	- Known issue:  repeatedly equipping/unequipping items that result in speed/dodge/defense
	  <= 0 allows those stats to be increased by 1 infinitely; This is a very tedious exploit.
	  Given the VERY minimal impact on gameplay, and exists to prevent division by 0, it's fine.
  - 'darray' datatype is a holdover from when everything was written in C; I did attempt to 
	  change all uses of this to std::vector, but it rapidly started having issues that were
	  taking too long to debug. So, darray remains a part of this codebase.
	- Known issue: it takes a weirdly long time for sub-menus to go away. Not sure why.
	- Known issue: there is a small 'memory leak' associated with ncurses. This is not actually
	  an issue, and is intended behavior for the library.